Kim Jong Il inspects KPA unit 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) - General Secretary Kim Jong Il  inspected KPA unit no. 744 honored with the title of the "O Jung Hup's Seventh Regiment."
 He was accompanied by KPA generals Ri Myong Su, Hyon Chol Hae and Pak Jae Gyong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Hearing a report on the situation from the commander of the unit, he acquainted himself in detail with the performance of the unit's duty. Then, he dropped in at the operation lecture room to see commanding officers in tactical training. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He noted with great satisfaction that the commanding officers of the unit, firmly armed with the Juche-based war methods of the WPK, are successfully performing their combat tasks with skillful command and that all the soldiers are growing to be combatants capable of undertaking any duties through diverse trainings and set forth highly important tasks to be fulfilled to further increase the combat power of the unit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The officers and men of the unit have been trained as matchless combat ranks more firmly equipped politically and ideologically and in military technique through the thorough implementation of the WPK's military line and the vigorous "movement for winning the title of the O Jung Hup's Seventh Regiment" in particular, thus bringing about a signal turn in increasing the combat power of the unit, he said, highly praising them for their achievements made in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Going round various places of the unit, he noted with high appreciation that the unit is conducting the revolutionary and class education in a unique manner in various forms and by diverse methods to suit the characteristic features of the young soldiers and exerting intellectual and persevering efforts to provide the soldiers with good living conditions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He met soldiers to examine their caps, uniforms and belts and other details before saying that as uniforms are one of the important indexes showing the spirit of the army, the commanding officers should always pay deep attention to them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then, he moved on to a company under the unit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Going round the entertainment and logistic facilities of the company, he took a meticulous care of the living of its soldiers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He stressed the need for all the commanding officers to pay primary attention to the logistic work to provide the dear soldiers courageously standing guard over the country with the best living conditions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He had a picture taken with the soldiers of the unit.

Macarthur's crimes under fire
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) -- The call of the South Korean people from all walks of life for the removal of the statue of Macarthur in Inchon is an eruption of the towering resentment of the nation against the U.S. imperialist aggressors and a reflection of their fixed will not to allow the aggressors and murderers to stay in South Korea.
 Rodong Sinmun today says this in a signed commentary. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The crime-woven history of Macarthur, who won an ill-fame as the chieftain of aggression and warmonger, is an epitome of the blood-stained history of the U.S. imperialists recorded with aggression, mass killings and plunder of Koreans. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was Macarthur who saved the Japanese emperor, the second world war criminal, and overlooked the Japanese imperialists' looting of historical and cultural relics of Korea and opposed their return. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He orchestrated the U.S. plan to start the Korean War and commanded this war of aggression before and after its start holding the posts of the commander of the U.S. forces in the far east and the commander of the "UN Forces". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He was the top-class war criminal, who advocated the use of A-bombs in Korea in a bid to save himself from his military incompetence and setbacks in the Korean War.   Nevertheless, he was painted as a "savior of Koreans" and his statue was erected in South Korea. This is bitter disgrace and tragedy of the nation.

Films on Kim Il Sung's revolutionary activities screened
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) -- Documentary films were screened in all parts of the DPRK on the occasion of the 8th anniversary of President Kim Il Sung's demise.
 Among them are "our people's honor of holding the great leader in high esteem", "always believing in people", "the great life in 1994" and "the great leader comrade Kim Il Sung is immortal". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They record the immortal revolutionary activities of the president who devoted all his efforts to the party, the revolution, the country and the people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Screening at cinema houses across the country are feature films "star of Korea", "the sun of the nation", "a summer at the Hwasong Uisuk School," "the forest sways" which depict the immortal revolutionary life of the president, and other films.

KCNA on Bush's war logic
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) -- The U.S. department of defense is planning to integrate the space command and the strategic command into a new command, according to the New York Times.
 In this connection, Xinhua News reported that the projected command will coordinate and command the U.S. missile warning network, the national Missile Defence System (MD) now in the making and capabilities to plan and mount attacks on nuclear and conventional weapons. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. Defense Department's plan poses a serious threat to world peace and security as it is a move of the U.S. hawkish forces to push increased spurs to the establishment of the MD and put the strategy of "preemptive attack" into practice. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, U.S. secretary of defence Rumsfeld in an interview with the Washington Times on July 2 said that the U.S. Defense Department will not deliberately set a "date for the deployment of the Missile Defense System" and that all the U.S. plans for the MD are at the stage of research and test designing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The assertion made by Rumsfeld pulling up someone over his increased "missile threat" to the united states is no more than a crafty scheme to justify the reckless war policy of the U.S. hawkish forces. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is advocating a new world strategy in a bid to put the world under its control, styling itself the "only super power" at the end of the Cold War. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The keynote of the U.S. strategy is a "preemptive attack" as it is aimed to neutralize other nuclear and missile powers through the MD, ensure sustained development and production of strategic and tactical nuclear weapons and deploy and use them in actual wars. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The present U.S. administration's self-opinionated war logic so-called Bush's war logic has already been put into practice. This is fully revealed in Bush's remarks about the "axis of evil" and his undisguised order to overthrow the legitimate regime in Iraq. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is more clearly evidenced by the integration of the space command and the strategic command projected by the U.S. Defense Department. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the international community allows the reckless war moves of the U.S. warmongers not only peace and stability of humankind but the long-standing human civilization will suffer a total destruction in the worldwide thermonuclear war in the 21st century.

Public presentation of foreign students held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) -- A public presentation of works written by foreign students studying at Kim Il Sung University under the title "great man and Korea" was held at the Taedonggang club for the diplomatic corps on July 5 on the occasion of the 8th anniversary of President Kim Il Sung's demise.
 Present there were foreign students studying at universities in Pyongyang. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The performers put on the stage poems, essays, memoirs and impressions reflecting ardent yearning and reverence for Kim Il Sung and the reality of the DPRK which is vigorously advancing to build a powerful nation under the ever-victorious army-based revolutionary leadership of Kim Jong Il. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They sang a chorus "the leader will always be with us", a female chorus "dear general, where are you", a male chorus "song of comradeship", a mixed chorus "we are one" and other Korean songs.

GIS' crimes against humanity in Korean War under fire
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 6 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun today carries a signed article condemning the monstrous crimes against humanity the U.S. imperialists committed by massacring innocent civilians by most brutal methods in the last Korean War.
 From the summer of 1950 to the next summer GIS mercilessly killed more than one million civilians in South Korea, whose number was much bigger than those killed in the whole period of a war. The number of civilians killed by them during the Korean war reached millions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In just 50 days of their stationing in Sinchon county after the Korean People's Army made a temporary strategic retreat GIS massacred more than 35,380 civilians or a quarter of its population. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The thrice-cursed crimes against humanity were perpetrated by the U.S. imperialist aggressors in the Korean War in wanton violation of international wartime laws and rules including the 1949 Geneva convention on wartime protection of civilians. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
They killed Koreans in cold blood wherever they went in Korea, the article says, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They even used germ weapons and chemical weapons to kill Koreans in violation of human morality and international conventions. they went the length of killing POWs of our side indiscriminately in gross breach of international laws and rules on POWs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialists are still watching for a chance to ignite a war against the DPRK, the article says, warning that if they finally start a war of aggression, the army and people of the DPRK will deal deadly retaliatory blows at them to wipe them out on this land to the last man and make them pay a thousand-fold price for the blood shed by Koreans.
